title: King Charles III diagnosed with cancer, postponing public duties
description: Buckingham Palace said the British king had begun regular treatments and would continue official business and paperwork.

title: Russia poised to bar only antiwar candidate from presidential race
description: Boris Nadezhdin, an antiwar candidate seeking to run in Russia’s presidential election, will probably be barred from the ballot.

title: Blinken arrives in Saudi Arabia amid a surge in regional violence
description: Secretary of State Antony Blinken is in the Middle East seeking to advance a potential hostage deal between Hamas and Israel. His first stop was Saudi Arabia.

title: Two men wanted to start a family. Soon, they could be outlaws.
description: The Italian government is trying to criminalize having children using surrogates abroad, a move that critics say targets same-sex couples.

title: Middle East conflict live updates: U.S. promises more retaliation against militias; Blinken to visit region
description: National security adviser Jake Sullivan said the strikes in Yemen, Iraq and Syria were “the beginning of our response” to the killing of three U.S. soldiers.

title: Behold, the bin chicken: Sydney’s stinky, grimy but (mostly) beloved bird
description: White ibises divide opinion Down Under. Some Aussies love them so much they get bin chicken tattoos. Others hate the dumpster divers and would like them culled.

title: One year after a devastating earthquake, Turkey tries to rebuild
description: Gaping holes where hundreds of buildings previously stood now dominate the country’s southern landscape.

title: A year along the vital river that flows through Ukraine’s heart
description: Photographer Ed Ram traveled the length of the river, from north to south, in the winter, spring, summer and fall, to reveal its vital role in a country at war.

title: China hands Australian writer suspended death sentence in spy case
description: Yang Hengjun, detained in China for more than five years, received a suspended sentence that can be commuted to life imprisonment after two years, a friend said.
